# ADR conventions

Every ADR uses **MADR** as seeded from `docs/_templates/ADR_TEMPLATE.md` and
lives at `docs/adr/ADR-NNNN-<slug>.md` with a stable four-digit ID.

## Required frontmatter

```yaml
title:            # "ADR-NNNN: <short decision title>"
adr:              # NNNN
status:           # Proposed | Accepted | Deferred | Superseded-by: ADR-XXXX | Future-Considered/Reserved
date:             # YYYY-MM-DD
owner:            # assignee name (or explicit unassigned marker in draft ADRs)
peer_reviewer:    # assignee name (SHOULD differ from owner; solo maintainer may self-review)
deciders:         # [names]
# Required when status == Deferred:
due_date:         # YYYY-MM-DD
# Required when status == Future-Considered/Reserved:
re_entry_criteria: # "<concrete trigger(s) that make this in-scope again>"
touch_points:      # [docs/ADRs that would need to be revisited]
```

## Status rules

- **Proposed** — draft; open for review.
- **Accepted** — signed off by peer reviewer; Change Log names the reviewer.
- **Deferred** — decision intentionally postponed. `owner` and `due_date`
  fields MUST be set. A Deferred ADR without both fails review.
- **Superseded-by** — another ADR replaces this one. Keep the file; update
  status to `Superseded-by: ADR-XXXX` and add a forward link.
- **Future-Considered/Reserved** — out of roadmap phases 1–5 scope but architecturally
  real. `re_entry_criteria` and `touch_points` MUST be filled in and the ADR
  MUST be listed in `docs/architecture/future-considerations.md`.

## Required sections

Status · Context · Decision drivers · Considered options · Decision outcome
(positive + negative consequences) · Validation · Pros/cons per option ·
Links · Change Log.

Validation is non-optional: every `Accepted` ADR states what would falsify it.
